-- PRESS DIGEST - Bulgaria - Aug 19
-- 
-- Tue Aug 19, 2014 02:57AM EDT
-- None



SOFIA, Aug 19 (Reuters) - These are some of the main stories in Bulgarian newspapers on Tuesday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

-- Bulgaria's Interim Energy Minister Vasil Shtonov has instructed state-owned Bulgarian Energy Holding (BEH) to discontinue all tendering and contracting procedures on the South Stream gas pipeline project until it is aligned with EU legislation (Trud, Standart, Presa, Capital daily, 24 Chasa, Duma). -- Interim Vice Premier Ekaterina Zaharieva said that the energy board, with participation of foreign experts, was planned to be set up next week. The board will aim to ensure that decisions concerning the multi-billion dollar projects on Bulgarian territory are transparent (Sega, 24 Chasa). -- The construction of a third bridge over the Danube River will cost between 200 million euros (266.92 million US dollar) and 270 million euros, said Elean Gagov, an expert at the ministry of regional development, adding the four options for the new bridge were Oryahovo - Bechet, Silistra - Calarasi, Ruse - Giurgiu, and Nikopol - Turnu Magurele -- Bulgarian miners have asked caretaker Prime Minister Georgi Bliznashki to lift the ban on shale gas extraction through hydraulic fracturing. They insisted shale gas would provide an opportunity for the diversification of supplies and for reducing prices of natural gas (Standart, Presa, Monitor, 24 Chasa, Duma). -- MEP and ex-journalist Nikolay Barekov's Bulgaria without Censorship has sealed a coalition agreement with Lider party. Barekov said he is trying to form a "big centrist patriotic bloc" (Trud, Standart, Presa, Sega, Duma).